Homework 2¶

Task 1¶

Part a¶

In the first task of the second homework, the aim is mainly about understanding the structure of a given data through PCA (Principle Component Analysis) and MDS (Multidimensional scheduling). The data that is used for this part is a Musk data that consists the features of given 475 molecule instances. These instances, by scientists, are divided into classes according to their feature values. F rom these classes, the scientists argue that the class is either a “Musk” type or “Non-Musk”. The main goal is to predict whether a given instance of a molecule is belong to “Musk” or “Non-musk” class.

I have took the features columns to understand how they represent the variance of the data (bag class and the bag id).

Then, I have applied PCA using "prcomp" function and by summarizing the pca, observed that about 75% of the difference between these data rows can be explained by the first 4 features. Therefore, I have chosen these 4 features to reflect the data instead of 166 features.

In [533]:
musk.pca <- prcomp(musk, retx=TRUE, center = FALSE,scale. = TRUE)

When I plot the Variances of Principal components, it is observed that the variances look like exponentially distributed. This is also another reason to choose first 4 components. The effect of the other features decreases smoothly.

After choosing the features to explain the data, I have looked at the relations between these features and plotted the features one by one to see if they are correlated and if they form groups according to their bag class.

The combinations of the features are plotted below. Additionally, the "red" color points specify "Non-musk" molecules when "blue" ones represent "Musks".

The figures below shows that there is no correlation between these components and they represent the molecules efficiently. For instance, one can see that the distribution of the blue and the red points depends on the x axis in the first plot.

Task 2¶

In the second task, I have requested to perform certain operations on images. The aim was to compress images using PCA.

Part 1¶

In the first part, I read and display the image of Mona Lisa with size of 256x256

In [312]:
require(jpeg)
monalisa <- readJPEG("mona lisa.jpg")
my_image <- as.raster(monalisa)
plot(my_image)

Part 2¶

a)¶

I have created the noise values and added them to the original pixel values and I took 1 for the new pixelss that exceeds 1.

In [346]:
noise<-monalisa
for (i in 1:256){
    for(j in 1:256){
        for(k in 1:3){
            noise[i:i,j:j,k:k] <-runif(1,min(monalisa),max(monalisa)/10)
        }
    }
}
In [348]:
noisy_monalisa<-monalisa+noise

for (i in 1:256){
    for(j in 1:256){
        for(k in 1:3){
            if(noisy_monalisa[i:i,j:j,k:k]>1)
           noisy_monalisa[i:i,j:j,k:k]<-1
        }
    }
}
new_image<-as.raster(noisy_monalisa)
plot(new_image)

b)¶

Then I display the Three colour factors seperately.

r<-apply(noisy_monalisa[,,1],2,rev)

Then I have used the data in the x vector of the pca object to display the components as images. In here, the x values are not range from 0 to 1. Therefore, I have applied Normalization.

In [547]:
first_component<-patches.pca$x[,1]
vector_comp1<-as.vector(t(first_component))
dim(vector_comp1)<-c(252,252)
normalize <- function(x) {
return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}
normalized_vector_comp1<-normalize(vector_comp1)
image_comp1<-as.raster(normalized_vector_comp1)
plot(image_comp1,)

Finally, it is observed that the plot of the first component shows that in each patch, if we take the component that is in the middle of the patch, most of the data will be represented. This representation level will decrease when we take the component from the bottom or the right of the patch. However, the informations of these components are still necessary in order to show the image using these components.
